Program 10: Proxy Server Setup & SSH Port Forwarding
System Requirement

2 Computers (Machine A and Machine B)

Linux (Ubuntu/Kali)

LAN or same WiFi network

PART 1 — Install Required Tools

Run on BOTH machines

sudo apt update
sudo apt install squid
sudo apt install lynx

Check installation:

squid -v
lynx -version
PART 2 — Configure IP Address
Machine 1
sudo ifconfig enp4s0 10.0.0.1 netmask 255.255.255.0
Machine 2
sudo ifconfig enp4s0 10.0.0.2 netmask 255.255.255.0

Check:

ifconfig

Test connection:

From Machine 2

ping 10.0.0.1
PART 3 — Configure Proxy Server

On both machines

Set proxy port 3128

export http_proxy=http://localhost:3128

Check variable:

echo $http_proxy
PART 4 — Test Proxy Using Lynx

Open website using terminal browser

lynx http://gnu.org

You should see GNU website in terminal.

This confirms Proxy Server working.

PART 5 — Create Local Web Server (Machine 1)

Create directory

mkdir /tmp/website

Go inside

cd /tmp/website

Create webpage

echo "Hi There" > index.html

Check file

cat index.html
PART 6 — Start Python Web Server

Run:

python3 -m http.server 8000 --bind 127.0.0.1

Output should show:

Serving HTTP on 127.0.0.1 port 8000

Important:

⚠️ This server is ONLY accessible locally on Machine 1.

PART 7 — Create SSH Tunnel (Machine 2)

Now access Machine 1 web server using SSH Port Forwarding

Run on Machine 2

ssh user@10.0.0.1 -v -L 127.0.0.1:6000:127.0.0.1:8000

Explanation:

Part	Meaning
ssh user@10.0.0.1	connect to Machine 1
-L	Local port forwarding
6000	client port
8000	server web port
PART 8 — Access the Web Server

On Machine 2

Run:

lynx http://127.0.0.1:6000

Output:

Hi There

This means SSH port forwarding works.

